<h3>Amines</h3>

<h5> A LEVEL </h5> @* Help users distinguish between Year 12 and Year 13 topics*@


<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Amines are organic compounds derived from ammonia (NH<sub>3</sub>) by replacing one or more hydrogen atoms with alkyl or aryl groups. They are classified as primary, secondary, or tertiary based on the number of substituents attached to the nitrogen atom.
</p>

<h2 style="color: navy; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Classification of Amines</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Primary Amine:</b> One hydrogen atom is replaced by an alkyl or aryl group. Example: Methylamine (CH<sub>3</sub>NH<sub>2</sub>).</li>
    <li><b>Secondary Amine:</b> Two hydrogen atoms are replaced. Example: Dimethylamine ((CH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub>NH).</li>
    <li><b>Tertiary Amine:</b> All three hydrogen atoms are replaced. Example: Trimethylamine ((CH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub>N).</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: navy; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">General Formula</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    The general formula of amines depends on their classification:
</p>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Primary amines:</b> RNH<sub>2</sub></li>
    <li><b>Secondary amines:</b> R<sub>2</sub>NH</li>
    <li><b>Tertiary amines:</b> R<sub>3</sub>N</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: navy; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Physical Properties</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Boiling Points:</b> Amines have relatively high boiling points due to hydrogen bonding (in primary and secondary amines). Tertiary amines lack N-H bonds and do not form hydrogen bonds, resulting in lower boiling points.</li>
    <li><b>Solubility:</b> Amines are soluble in water due to hydrogen bonding. Solubility decreases with increasing chain length.</li>
    <li><b>Odor:</b> Many amines have a fishy odor.</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: navy; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Basicity of Amines</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Amines act as bases due to the lone pair of electrons on the nitrogen atom. They can accept protons to form ammonium ions.
</p>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Strength of Basicity:</b> The basicity depends on the availability of the lone pair:
        <ul>
            <li>Alkyl groups increase electron density on nitrogen, enhancing basicity.</li>
            <li>Aryl groups decrease basicity due to delocalization of the lone pair into the aromatic ring.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: navy; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Reactions of Amines</h2>
<ol style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Reaction with Acids:</b> Amines react with acids to form ammonium salts. Example:
        <code>CH<sub>3</sub>NH<sub>2</sub> + HCl → CH<sub>3</sub>NH<sub>3</sub>Cl</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Reaction with Halogenoalkanes:</b> Amines react with halogenoalkanes to form secondary or tertiary amines or quaternary ammonium salts. Example:
        <code>CH<sub>3</sub>NH<sub>2</sub> + CH<sub>3</sub>Cl → (CH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub>NH + HCl</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Reaction with Acyl Chlorides:</b> Amines react with acyl chlorides to form amides. Example:
        <code>CH<sub>3</sub>NH<sub>2</sub> + CH<sub>3</sub>COCl → CH<sub>3</sub>CONHCH<sub>3</sub> + HCl</code>.
    </li>
</ol>

<h2 style="color: navy; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Tests for Amines</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Litmus Test:</b> Amines turn red litmus paper blue, indicating basicity.</li>
    <li><b>Reaction with Copper(II) Ions:</b> Amines form a deep blue complex with copper(II) ions in aqueous solution.</li>
</ul>

